SIMPLE: secret
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Secret
<hw>Se"cret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>secret</ets>
(cf. Sp. & Pg. <ets>secreto</ets>, It. <ets>secreto</ets>,
<ets>segreto</ets>), fr. L. <ets>secretus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>secernere</ets> to put apart, to separate. See <er>Certain</er>,
and cf. <er>Secrete</er>, <er>Secern</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Hidden; concealed; <as>as, <ex>secret</ex> treasure;
<ex>secret</ex> plans; a <ex>secret</ex> vow</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>secret</qex> things belong unto the Lord our God; but
those things which are revealed belong unto us.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xxix.
29.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Withdrawn from general intercourse or notice; in
retirement or secrecy; secluded.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There, <qex>secret</qex> in her sapphire cell,⟦br⟧
He with the Nais wont to dwell.</q> <rj><qau>Fenton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Faithful to a secret; not inclined to divulge or
betray confidence; secretive.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Secret</qex> Romans, that have spoke the word,⟦br⟧
And will not palter.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Separate; distinct.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They suppose two other divine hypostases superior thereunto, which
were perfectly <qex>secret</qex> from matter.</q>
<rj><qau>Cudworth.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Hidden; concealed; secluded; retired; unseen;
unknown; private; obscure; recondite; latent; covert; clandestine;
privy. See <er>Hidden</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Secret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Secret
<hw>Se"cret</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>secret</ets> (cf. Pr.
<ets>secret</ets>, Sp. & Pg. <ets>secreto</ets>, It. <ets>secreto</ets>,
<ets>segreto</ets>), from L. <ets>secretum</ets>. See <er>Secret</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something studiously concealed; a
thing kept from general knowledge; what is not revealed, or not to be
revealed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To tell our own <qex>secrets</qex> is often folly; to communicate
those of others is treachery.</q> <rj><qau>Rambler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1301 pr=PCP --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A thing not discovered; what is unknown or
unexplained; a mystery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All <qex>secrets</qex> of the deep, all nature's works.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The parts which modesty and
propriety require to be concealed; the genital organs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In secret</b></col>, <cd>in a private place; in privacy
or secrecy; in a state or place not seen; privately.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bread eaten <qex>in secret</qex> is pleasant.</q> <rj><qau>Prov.
ix. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Secret</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Secret
<hw>Se"cret</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To keep
secret.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Secretage</ent>⟦br⟧
